export const DOC_01 = `ГЛАВНОЕ РАЗВЕДЫВАТЕЛЬНОЕ УПРАВЛЕНИЕ
ГЛАВНЫЙ ШТАБ ВООРУЖЁННЫХ СИЛ СССР
СОВЕРШЕННО СЕКРЕТНО — ЭКЗЕМПЛЯР 1 ИЗ 3

[TRANSLATION — CERTIFIED GCHQ 1994]
GRU DIRECTORATE OF SPECIAL PROGRAMS
AUTHORIZATION BRIEF — PROJECT I (ИСТИНА / TRUTH)
CLASSIFICATION: EYES ONLY — DIRECTOR LEVEL
DATE OF AUTHORIZATION: 14 MARCH 1957
DOCUMENT REF: GRU/SP/57-114-I

---

BACKGROUND

This brief constitutes formal authorization for the
initiation of Project I (designated ISTINA — Truth)
under the directorship of Dr. Arkady Nikolayevich
Sorokin, Senior Research Officer, Neurological
Applications Division, GRU Special Programs.

The strategic objective of Project I is the
engineering of operationally viable human subjects
who are incapable of experiencing fear as a
psychological or physiological state. The
application of such subjects to deep-cover
operational roles, sustained interrogation
resistance, and high-attrition field assignments
is considered to have significant strategic value
in the current geopolitical climate.

Project I is not a psychological conditioning
program. It is not a pharmacological suppression
program. It is a developmental engineering program.
The distinction is considered operationally
significant. Conditioned or suppressed fear can
be unlocked by sufficient stimulus. Absent fear
cannot.

---

SCIENTIFIC BASIS (SUMMARY — FULL BRIEF: GRU/SP/57-114-I/ANNEX A)

Fear response in humans is primarily mediated by
the amygdaloid complex — bilateral almond-shaped
nuclei embedded in the medial temporal lobe.
Destruction of the amygdala in adult subjects
produces significant but incomplete fear
suppression and is accompanied by unacceptable
cognitive degradation.

Dr. Sorokin's hypothesis, developed across eleven
years of animal research, proposes that targeted
chemical suppression of amygdala neurogenesis
during embryonic week 11 — the critical window
of amygdaloid cell proliferation — will produce
subjects in whom the amygdaloid complex is
structurally absent from birth, without the
collateral damage associated with post-natal
destruction.

Early animal trials (rats, 1951-53; primates,
1954-56) confirm suppression of fear behavior
in surviving subjects. Survival rates across
animal trials: 31%. GRU considers this rate
acceptable for initial human trials.

Dr. Sorokin estimates human survival rate will
improve with refined delivery methodology.
This estimate is noted but does not constitute
a program guarantee.

---

AUTHORIZATION SCOPE

This document authorizes:

1. Procurement of fourteen (14) viable human
   embryos for developmental intervention.
   Procurement methodology is the operational
   responsibility of GRU Section 7 and is
   outside the scope of this document.

2. Full laboratory establishment at CLOSED
   FACILITY 12, AKADEMGORODOK COMPLEX,
   NOVOSIBIRSK OBLAST. Facility designation
   classified. Personnel access: Dr. Sorokin
   plus authorized staff only.

3. Developmental intervention at week 11
   of embryonic development using the Sorokin
   chemical suppression protocol (full details:
   GRU/SP/57-114-I/ANNEX B).

4. Gestation and post-natal development
   of surviving subjects to an assessment
   age of no less than 36 months.

5. Operational assessment by GRU Directorate
   at conclusion of initial development phase.
   Disposal or operational integration of
   surviving subjects at GRU discretion.

---

PERSONNEL

DIRECTOR: Dr. A.N. Sorokin
DEPUTY DIRECTOR: Dr. E.M. Voss
MEDICAL OFFICER: Dr. P.I. Kurakin (obstetrics)
SECURITY LIAISON: [REDACTED]
FACILITY ADMINISTRATOR: [REDACTED]
AUTHORIZED SUPPORT STAFF: 4

All personnel are subject to Closed Program
restrictions. No communication outside Facility 12
regarding Project I content, personnel, or outcomes.
Violation constitutes criminal offense under
Article 64, Criminal Code of the RSFSR.

---

OUTCOMES REPORTING

Quarterly progress reports to GRU Directorate
via secure channel only.
Final assessment report upon conclusion of
initial development phase.

Sorokin is authorized to terminate the program
at his discretion if continuation poses
unmanageable operational security risk.

In the event of program termination, all
subjects — surviving or otherwise — are to be
disposed of per Facility 12 Protocol BD-7.
No subject is to leave Facility 12 alive.

---

AUTHORIZATION SIGNATURES

[SIGNED] DIRECTOR, GRU SPECIAL PROGRAMS
[SIGNED] DEPUTY DIRECTOR, GRU
[SIGNED] DR. A.N. SOROKIN — PROGRAM ACCEPTANCE

DOCUMENT ENDS.

ARCHIVE NOTE: This document was present in the
Stillwater Archive at the time of Operation
Stillwater's constitution. Upload date precedes
the operation by 8 months and 14 days.
Uploader: UNIDENTIFIED.`;

export const DOC_02 = `PROJECT I — SENIOR RESEARCHER PERSONAL LOG
DR. A.N. SOROKIN
FACILITY 12, NOVOSIBIRSK OBLAST
JANUARY 1961

NOTE: These pages were recovered from Facility 12
following its decommissioning in 1963. They are
reproduced here in full. Minor translation
amendments for clarity are marked [T].

---

9 JANUARY 1961 — 07:14

Subject F-13 is now 48 hours old.

I want to record this carefully because I am
not yet certain what I am looking at, and I
have learned in thirty years of research that
the moment before certainty is when a man
is most likely to see clearly.

The other twelve [T: surviving subjects at time
of writing] show standard neonatal behavior
within parameters we expected. Reduced startle
response. Lowered cortisol on stimulus
introduction. The amygdaloid suppression
appears to be functioning as the protocol
predicted, though I reserve full assessment
for the 36-month mark.

F-13 is different.

I noticed it first during the morning feed
rotation. The nursing staff work in a fixed
order: Borova enters first, Marchetti second,
Lena third. This has been the pattern for 48
hours. Yesterday I varied the order without
informing the staff — I asked Lena to enter
first.

F-13's eyes tracked to the door before Lena
reached it.

This could be coincidence. Sound carries in
this corridor. Footsteps are distinguishable
if you know what to listen for. I noted it
and said nothing.

This morning I varied the order again. Marchetti
first. Then I waited.

F-13 tracked to the door at the exact moment
Marchetti's footstep pattern began — a full
four seconds before she was visible.

He recognized her gait. At 48 hours old.

I have no framework for this. The amygdala
suppression should not have produced this. I
am going to continue observation and say
nothing to Voss until I understand what I
am seeing.

---

9 JANUARY 1961 — 21:55

I went back to the observation window at 21:00.
The ward was dark. F-13 was the only subject
still awake.

He was looking at the window.

The observation glass is one-way. Voss had
it installed at the start of the program
precisely so we could observe without
influencing subject behavior. There is no
light source on our side. There is no
reflection. There is no physical cue that
a window exists there rather than a wall.

He was looking at the window.

Not at the wall. At the specific panel of
glass behind which I was standing.

I moved left. His gaze moved left.
I moved right. His gaze moved right.

I left the observation room and I sat in the
corridor for approximately twenty minutes
before I wrote this down.

I have a hypothesis. I am not ready to write
it here yet. I want to observe one more day.

---

10 JANUARY 1961 — 08:30

I told Voss this morning, before the feed
rotation, that I wanted to run a small test.
I did not tell her what I suspected.

We stood together behind the observation glass.

I asked her: "What do you see?"

She said: "He's awake. He's facing the window."

I said: "Yes."

I asked her: "Does that seem unusual to you?"

She said: "All of them face the light sources
when they're awake. The window — "

I said: "Voss. There's no light on this side."

She was quiet for a while.

I said: "What else do you see?"

She said: "He's not doing anything. He's just
looking."

I said: "Yes. Just looking. At exactly where
we are standing."

We watched him for an hour. He did not look
away. He did not fall asleep. He did not
cry or fuss. He simply watched the glass
with an expression I do not have a word for.

Not curiosity. Curiosity implies uncertainty.

More like recognition.

At 36 hours old, F-13 appears to have a
functional model of the space he occupies —
including the space he cannot directly
perceive — that updates in real time
based on stimulus tracking.

What I believe — and I want to be very careful
with this word, because I am aware of how it
sounds — is that F-13 encodes everything.

Every sound. Every footfall. Every variation
in airflow. Every face. Every sequence of
events. He does not experience it and store
a degraded impression of it the way a normal
infant would. He stores it whole.

He stores it whole, and he uses it.

He knew I was behind that glass because he
had already built a complete map of every
person in this facility from the sounds they
make and the patterns they follow, and that
map told him where I was.

He is 48 hours old.

---

10 JANUARY 1961 — 19:00

Received the termination order.

GRU directive, dated today. All thirteen
surviving subjects are to be disposed of
per Protocol BD-7. Program is to be
dissolved. Reason given: strategic
reprioritization. No further detail.

I have read the directive three times.

Formal acknowledgment is required within
24 hours.

I am going to sit with this tonight.

---

11 JANUARY 1961 — 03:12

I have written and destroyed four versions
of this entry.

Here is what I know: F-13 is not what I
expected to create. He is not what the
program was designed to create. He is not
a fear-absent operative candidate. He is
something I do not have words for yet,
and I am 58 years old and I have spent
my career looking for things worth not
having words for yet, and I have never
found one until now.

Here is what I also know: The directive
is lawful. Protocol BD-7 is the correct
procedure. I have signed the acceptance.
The night workers have their orders.

I am going to bed.

I have decided not to visit the ward
tonight.

---

11 JANUARY 1961 — 09:55

Received and filed confirmation of disposal
procedures.

Baryshev and Volkov handled the night shift.

Confirmation form BD-7/CONF has not been
filed as of this writing. I have sent
a reminder to the administrative office.

I expect it will come through today.

---

ARCHIVE NOTE: BD-7/CONF was never filed.
The discrepancy was noted in a 1962 audit,
flagged as administrative error, and
classified as unresolved.
The file remained open.
No follow-up action was taken.`;

