export const DOC_04 = `[HANDWRITTEN — recovered from Voss apartment,
Novosibirsk, during routine security sweep,
March 1963. Voss had resigned from Facility 12
in February 1961 citing personal reasons.
She died in 1971. Cause of death: recorded
as pneumonia. She was 44 years old.

Translation certified. Handwriting analysis
confirms authorship. Original pages held
by GRU Records — location current unknown.

These notes were not addressed to anyone.
They appear to have been written for herself.]

---

12 JANUARY 1961

The program is over. Sorokin filed the
confirmation this morning and that was that.
Thirty years of his work. Eleven years of
mine. Over before breakfast.

I should write about the science.
I am going to write about F-13 instead.

---

His eyes.

I have been trying to find a way to describe
them that doesn't make me sound unwell and
I cannot. So I'll just write it plainly
and whoever reads this — if anyone ever
reads this — can make of it what they like.

He didn't look at things the way infants
look at things.

Infants search. Their eyes move across a
face looking for information — the mouth,
the eyes, the edges. They are building
something, constructing understanding from
pieces. You can see them doing it.
It's beautiful. It's recognizable.

F-13 didn't search.

When he looked at you, he looked at you
as though he had already finished.
As though the looking was not how he was
learning about you — it was something else.
Something more like acknowledgment.

I noticed it on day one and I told myself
it was projection. Thirty years of this
work and you start to see things.

Then Sorokin told me what he had been
observing with the observation window,
and I went and stood behind that glass,
and F-13 looked at me.

Not at the glass. At me.

He adjusted when I moved. He tracked me
through a wall.

So I ran my own test. I varied the staff
entry order six times across two days.
I varied the time of each entry. I changed
the staff uniforms so there was no visual
cue even if somehow the glass wasn't
doing what we needed it to do.

He knew every time.

Not sometimes. Every time.

He knew who was coming before they arrived.
He knew where Sorokin was standing in the
dark. He knew where I was. He had built —
at 72 hours old — a complete and accurate
model of every person in that facility and
he was updating it in real time from
information we couldn't even identify.

Sorokin's hypothesis is that the amygdala
suppression had an unexpected secondary
effect on memory encoding. That without
the fear-processing structure filtering
and prioritizing input, everything gets
recorded. Everything. With full fidelity.
No hierarchy, no emotion, no degradation.
Every sound, every pattern, every face —
stored perfectly from the moment of birth.

He's probably right. He's usually right.

But I went further in my thinking, sitting
up last night with the lights off because
I couldn't sleep.

If every moment is recorded with total
fidelity — not reconstructed, not
summarized, but stored — then he doesn't
have memories the way we have memories.

We have summaries. We have impressions.
We have the emotional residue of things
that happened.

He has the things themselves.

Every moment he has ever lived is still
happening somewhere inside him, perfectly
preserved, perfectly accessible. He is
simultaneously three days old and every
age he will ever be, and he always will be.

I don't know what that does to a person.
I don't know if it does anything to a
person, or if the word person is even
doing the work we need it to do here.

---

I heard the incinerator running last night.
Sub-level 2 is directly below my lab.
You can feel it in the floor more than
you can hear it.

I did not go downstairs.

I am writing this and then I am going to
resign in the morning and I am going to
go home and I am never going to think
about this again.

---

[UNDATED POSTSCRIPT — written in different ink,
later date unknown. Pen pressure noticeably
heavier than the body of the notes.]

He remembered my face.

God help whoever finds him next.`;
